				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">What's so hard about getting NES development tools set up in GNU/Linux? To set up an environment to build my projects, all you need to do (assuming a Debian descendant) is <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">sudo apt-get install build-essential python-imaging gimp fceux</tt>, install cc65 from source, and download a project template for your chosen mapper. The foremost thing I have to use Wine for is FCEUX's debugger (and the recent versions of FCEUX that support mapper 28), and I use Wine instead of Windows because it's cheaper than running Windows in a VM in Linux or Linux in a VM in Windows, both RAM-wise and license-wise.<br /><br />As for counting utilities on RHDN, a lot of those are designed for making mods to existing proprietary NES games. If you are creating an original NES game from scratch, you probably don't need a specialized editor for some other game's script or map format.</div>

