						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Banshaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I tried linux once in a while with every new version of Fedora and everytime I start to configure the UI in KDE or wathever, I always find a way to crash X windows. Maybe it's because of Fedora but still... That kinds of turned me off. And don't propose unbutu, for some reason, I don't like it. The only Windows Manager I liked was XFCE (I think).</div><br />One of the things lidnariq recommended is exactly what's on my laptop. Xubuntu is an Ubuntu variant that comes with Xfce desktop instead of the Unity that a lot of people love to hate.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I got tired about linux because I always had to figure out what to configure next to make something work, because it never worked well every time you try to install something (dependencies, whatever).</div><br />Ubuntu and other .deb-based\ distributions make this easy. If a program is in a repository, and you're installing it through apt-get or an apt frontend such as Ubuntu Software Center, all the dependencies are handled for you &quot;automagically&quot;. I've been told it's a little rougher with Fedora or other .rpm-based distributions, or when you're compiling something from source code (like cc65).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">ccovell wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Specifically, modern Windows borders are turning into the equivalent of puffy-kneed obese people.</div><br />Is that better or worse than roly-poly people with no feet?<br /><img src="https://lh3.ggpht.com/_QTSwZpzPuWQ/SyLvmZr1SpI/AAAAAAAABCs/deDPMTAvatg/s320/weebles.jpg" alt="Image" /><br />Pictured: &quot;Weebles&quot; toys (mid-2000s iteration). Clockwise from top left: Demby, Diddy, Noomie, Plug, Zeebo, Tooey.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Banshaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'm derailing the thread so I will stop here!</div><br />It's not <em>quite</em> a derail, as by now, Xfce is probably the best choice among widely used desktop environments for people who want something remotely similar to Windows XP through 7.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I love installing OS and play with them, I just don't have much time these days for &quot;that kind of geeky fun&quot;</div><br />I'm glad I rediscovered Linux in a brief moment when I had time for geeky fun. On a whim, I tried to get Puppy working on a hideously obsolete laptop, and then when a relative's computer broke, I used Puppy to get it at least browsing the web until it could be repaired. Once the new hard drive was in place, I installed Ubuntu, and that computer is still in service as my cousin's home server.</div>

